    "## Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Among full-time undergraduate students enrolled in on-campus, in-person courses, is country GDP per capita (PPP) associated with **(1) students’ self-reported frequency of ChatGPT use for schoolwork (Rarely–Extensively)** and **(2) whether students use ChatGPT relatively more for schoolwork learning support (e.g., explanations, summaries, study help) versus schoolwork assignment production (e.g., writing, coding, generating deliverables)**?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "AI has the potential to improve a wide range of fields and these industries may vary depending on the country. For example, in Kenya, AI is utilized to analyze the soil and crop conditions in agriculture.<a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1) On the other hand, the healthcare industry in South Africa utilizes AI to better understand and meet patient needs.<a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1) AI powered tools have substantially reduced human errors in such fields which require precise calculations, leading to a rapid development of new technology, thus enhancing a country’s economic growth. Vice versa, the economic state of a country has the potential to shape how AI is used.\n",
    "\n",
    "While AI has been a tool to improve the economic state of a country, it also has improved our daily lives by conveniently summarizing information at the tips of our fingers. With an increase in AI investment contributing significantly to the GDP growth since 2014<a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>2</sup>](#cite_note-2), a majority of students from various fields, surveyed between late 2023 and early 2024, believe that using AI improves learning and assignment execution in general<a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>3</sup>](#cite_note-3). However, a portion of the surveyed students expressed concerns over AI’s reliability and ethicalness within the academic setting.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite its benefit for the overall global development, AI has the potential to backfire. With an increase in AI usage comes an increase in concerns over how AI is utilized as a tool. In prior research and analysis, results reflected the trade off of using generative AI, a declination in critical thinking. In the study conducted by Kosmyna et al<a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>4</sup>](#cite_note-4), essays produced by participants in the LLM group reflected weak variability compared to the participants in the Brain-only group and the Search Engine group.\n",
    "\n",
    "With the variables of economic utilizations of AI and AI’s effects on human cognition, does a country’s development determine AI usage, especially in students? Specifically, does a country’s development relate to student usage of AI, the ways in which it is used as well as how much it is used?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "1. <a name=\"cite_note-1\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-1) Folorunso, A., Olanipekun, K., Adewumi, T., & Samuel, B. (2024). *A policy framework on AI usage in developing countries and its impact. Global Journal of Engineering and Technology Advances, 21(01), 154–166.* https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Adebola-Folorunso/publication/385559435_A_policy_framework_on_AI_usage_in_developing_countries_and_its_impact/links/672ac69d5852dd723caaf782/A-policy-framework-on-AI-usage-in-developing-countries-and-its-impact.pdf \n",
    "2. <a name=\"cite_note-2\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-2) Rubinton, H., & Patro, B. A. (2026, January 12). *Tracking AI’s contribution to GDP growth. Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, On the Economy.* https://www.stlouisfed.org/on-the-economy/2026/jan/tracking-ai-contribution-gdp-growth\n",
    "3. <a name=\"cite_note-3\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-3) Ravšelj, D., Keržič, D., Tomaževič, N., Umek, L., Brezovar, N., & Aristovnik, A. (2025). *Higher education students’ perceptions of ChatGPT: A global study of early reactions.* PLOS ONE, 20(2), e0315011. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0315011\n",
    "4. <a name=\"cite_note-4\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-4) Kosmyna, N., Hauptmann, E., Yuan, Y. T., Situ, J., Liao, X.-H., Beresnitzky, A. V., Braunstein, I., & Maes, P. (2025). Your brain on ChatGPT: Accumulation of cognitive debt when using an AI assistant for essay writing task (arXiv:2506.08872v1) [Preprint]. arXiv. https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.08872v1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We predict a dual pattern between a country’s economic development and how students use ChatGPT for schoolwork. Specifically, we predict that higher-education students in more economically developed countries—measured using **GDP per capita (PPP)**—will report using ChatGPT **more often** for schoolwork. We also predict that, among students who use ChatGPT for schoolwork, students in **less developed (lower-income) countries** will use it relatively **more for assignment production** (drafting/writing/coding/generating deliverables), while students in **more developed (higher-income) countries** will use it relatively **more for learning support** (tutoring/explanations/summaries).\n",
    "\n",
    "Our target group is **full-time undergraduate students** enrolled in **on-campus, in-person courses**, so we will narrow the dataset to only respondents who match this population.\n",
    "\n",
    "We expect this pattern because access and adoption tend to be higher in wealthier countries, including more reliable internet access and fewer barriers to using ChatGPT (including language barriers). In lower-income settings, higher academic pressure and fewer support resources may push students toward using ChatGPT to produce deliverables. In contrast, in some higher-income settings, stricter academic integrity norms may discourage using ChatGPT to generate final assignments and instead encourage using it for learning support.\n",
    "\n",
    "To examine this, we will use the self-reported survey data on (1) **how often students use ChatGPT for schoolwork** and (2) **what tasks they use it for**. For task type, we will group items into two categories. “Assignment production” will include tasks like **academic writing, professional writing, creative writing, and coding assistance**. “Learning support” will include tasks like **summarizing, calculations help, study assistance, and research assistance**. We will create a **Production score** (the average of production items) and a **Learning score** (the average of learning-support items). Then, among respondents who report using ChatGPT for schoolwork, we will label each student as **Production**, **Learning**, or **Mixed** based on which score is higher. \n",
    "\n",
    "We will then examine whether there is a relationship between a country’s **GDP per capita (PPP)** and (1) students’ **frequency of use** (Rarely, Occasionally, Moderately, Considerably, Extensively), and (2) their **task orientation**(Production vs Learning vs Mixed), based on whether their Production score or Learning score is higher. Our hypothesis will be supported if higher GDP per capita is associated with higher reported frequency and a more learning-support-oriented pattern, while lower GDP per capita is associated with lower frequency but a more production-oriented pattern.\n"
   ]
  },
